 Byzantine Papacy]]\n[[Category:6th-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:6th-century Christian theologians]]\n[[Category:6th-century Italian writers]]\n[[Category:6th-century Latin writers]]\n[[Category:6th-century popes]]\n[[Category:7th-century archbishops]]\n[[Category:7th-century Byzantine people]]\n[[Category:7th-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:7th-century Christian saints]]\n[[Category:7th-century Christian theologians]]\n[[Category:7th-century Italian writers]]\n[[Category:7th-century Latin writers]]\n[[Category:7th-century popes]]\n[[Category:Angelic visionaries]]\n[[Category:Benedictine popes]]\n[[Category:Benedictine saints]]\n[[Category:Church Fathers]]\n[[Category:Diplomats of the Holy See]]\n[[Category:Doctors of the Church]]\n[[Category:Gregorian mission]]\n[[Category:Italian Benedictines]]\n[[Category:Italian Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:Italian popes]]\n[[Category:Italian Roman Catholic writers]]\n[[Category:Last of the Romans]]\n[[Category:Medieval Italian saints]]\n[[Category:Medieval Italian theologians]]\n[[Category:Papal Apocrisiarii to Constantinople]]\n[[Category:Papal saints]]\n[[Category:Patristic mystics]]\n[[Category:Pre-Reformation saints of the Lutheran liturgical calendar]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic mystics]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic writers]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic theologians]]\n[[Category:Urban prefects of Rome]]\n[[Category:Popes]]\n", "name_user": "Ouah", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix typo \"including\" instead of \"Including\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pope_Gregory_I"}
{"title_page": "Saint Alvia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Saint Alvia\n| image                 =\n| caption            =\n| image_size            =\n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = The Saint Alvia Cartel\n| origin              = [[Burlington, Ontario|Burlington]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]\n| genre               = [[Rock music|Rock]]<br />[[Punk rock|Punk]]<br />[[Reggae]]\n| years_active        = 2005\u20132013\n| label               = [[Stomp Records|Stomp]]<br />[[Warner Music Canada]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Jersey (band)|Jersey]], [[Grade (band)|Grade]], [[Boys Night Out (band)|Boys Night Out]], The Video Dead (band)\n| website                 = [http://www.saintalvia.com Saint Alvia]\n| current_members     = Greg Taylor<br />Ben Rispin<br />Matt Richmond<br />Greg Fisher<br />Jon Laurin<br />Adam Michael\n}}\n\n'''Saint Alvia''', formerly '''The Saint Alvia Cartel''',<ref name=\"chartattack.com\"/> was a band formed in 2005 from [[Burlington, Ontario|Burlington]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]].  The band's self-titled debut album was nominated for a [[Juno Award for Rock Album of the Year]] at the [[2008 Juno Awards]].<ref name=\"junoawards.ca\"/>\n\n==History==\nSaint Alvia was formed by Rob Pasalic (formerly of [[Boys Night Out (band)|Boys Night Out]]) and Greg Taylor (formerly of [[Jersey (band)|Jersey]] and [[Grade (band)|Grade]]). The band is named after [[Ernest Alvia Smith]], Canada's last living recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]] for valor in World War II.\n\nWith roots in punk rock, the band drew inspiration from other genres which included rock and roll, blues, soul, dancehall reggae, country, new wave and hip hop. After recording and releasing demo tracks via MySpace in 2006, the band was signed to Montreal's Stomp Records and released their self-titled debut album in May 2006. The lead single \"Don't Wanna Wait Forever\" was released in the summer of 2007 and went into the Top 20 for Modern Rock Radio in Canada.\n\nThe band followed the 2007 release with 2008's critically acclaimed ''Between the Lines''.\n\nSaint Alvia played their final show on 7 December 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Destrukto|title=Burlington\u2019s Saint Alvia announce farewell show and final album|url=http://www.canadianmusicnews.com/zine/2013/12/06/new-releases/burlingtons-saint-alvia-announce-farewell-show-and-final-album/|website=Canadian Music News|accessdate=31 August 2016|date=6 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThey reunited [at least] one last time for [[Walk off the Earth]]'s Mike Taylor's Memorial and Tribute Concert<ref>{{cite news |title=Watch Mike \"Beard Guy\" Taylor Memorial and Tribute Concert |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F15MFWSafFY |accessdate=15 February 2019 |publisher=CBC Music}}</ref>\n\n==Members==\n* Greg Taylor \u2013 Vocals / Guitar\n* Ben Rispin \u2013 Vocals\n* Matt Richmond \u2013 Drums / Vocals\n* Greg Fisher \u2013 Guitar / Vocals\n* Jon Laurin \u2013 Keyboards\n* Adam Michael \u2013 Bass, Backing Vocals\n\n==Former members==\n* Brandon Bliss \u2013 Keyboards / Vocals\n* Rob Pasalic \u2013 Vocals / Guitar\n* Chuck Coles \u2013 Bass\n* Mike Casarin \u2013 Bass\n\n==Additional musicians==\n* Fatty McGinty of the Creepshow- Trombone (Try To Forget)\n* John Coombs of The Next Best Thing \u2013 Trumpet (Try To Forget)\n* Adam Michaels  \u2013 Guitar (Stones On The Road)\n* Jon Atley \u2013 Bongoes (Don't Wanna Wait Forever)\n* Laura Jane Bradfield \u2013 Vocals (Blonde Kryptonite)\n'''Between The Lines'''\n* Fatty McGinty of The Creepshow \u2013 Trombone (Decadencia De Civilizacion, Roll With it)\n* Ricky Snips of The Snips \u2013 Trumpet (Decadencia De Civilizacion, Roll With it,Mornings In Feng Tu)\n* Wade Mcneil of Alexisonfire/Black Lungs \u2013 Additional Vocals ( Mornings in Feng Tu)\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n*''The Saint Alvia Cartel \u2013 4 song demo'' (2006 \u2013 Self Released)\n*''The Saint Alvia Cartel'' (2007 \u2013 Stomp Records)\n*''Between The Lines'' (2008 \u2013 Stomp Records)\n*''Jonxer 7-inch'' (2010 \u2013 Paper and Plastic)\n*''Static Psalms'' (2013 \u2013 Divergent Recordings)\n\n===Compilations===\n*''Borrowed Tunes \u2013 A Neil Young Tribute'' (Thrasher)\n*'' Juiceboxdotcom.com compilation \u2013 Don't Wanna Wait Forever'' ( Phil B's Sunshine Remix)\n\n===Singles===\n\n* ''Don't Wanna Wait Forever''\n* ''Time To Go''\n* ''Blonde Kryptonite''\n* ''Between The Lines''\n* ''Walk Before You Run DMC''\n* ''Romeo''\n* ''Mothers Day''\n* ''Define Me''\n\n==Awards==\n* [[2009 MuchMusic Video Awards]]: Best Post-Production ( The Saint Alvia Cartel \u2013 \"Blonde Kryptonite\" (post-production: Nick Flook, Mike Sevigny & Jeff Middleton)) \u2013 Nominated\n* [[Juno Awards of 2008]]: Rock Album of the Year(The Saint Alvia Cartel) \u2013 Nominated\n* [[Juno Awards of 2009]]: Best Video \u2013 Blonde Kryptonite ( Directed by Davin Black)-Nominated\n* [[2009 FU Awards]]: \u2013 Best FU song ( Romeo)- Nominated\n* [[2008 Hamilton Music Awards]]: Best Punk Album of the Year \u2013 Nominated\n* [[2008 Hamilton Music Awards]]: Video of The Year ( Between The Lines Directed by Davin Black,Produced by Ben Rispin) \u2013 Nominated\n* [[2007 Hamilton Music Awards]]: Best New Band \u2013 Won\n\n==Interviews==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081013042022/http://www.torontomusicscene.ca/interviews/saint-alvia-s-new-album-out-next-tuesday-ups-the-pol.html Saint Alvia\u2019s new album out next Tuesday ups the politics] Interview with TorontoMusicScene.ca\n*[https://archive.is/20130115093940/http://www.exclaim.ca/articles/multiarticlesub.aspx?csid1=112&csid2=4&fid1=26077 Saint Alvia Cartel article] July 2007\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090104000425/http://hangout.altsounds.com/features/100217-saint-alvia-cartel-interview-with-greg-taylor.html Altsounds: interview]\n*[https://archive.is/20080509131758/http://www.truthexplosion.com/live/interviews/interviews.php?id=232 Truth Explosion: article]\n*[http://www.supernova.com/thesaintalviacartel Supernova: article]\n*[http://www.citynews.ca/news/news_19435.aspx City News: article]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of bands from Canada]]\n{{Portal|Music|Canada}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist\n| colwidth = 30em\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"chartattack.com\">\n{{cite news\n |title       = Saint Alvia Shorten Name\n |author      = Erik Leijon\n |url         = http://www.chartattack.com/news/59800/saint-alvia-shorten-name\n |agency      = {{URL|chartattack.com}}\n |newspaper   = [[Chart (magazine)|Chart]]\n |publisher   = Chart Communications\n |location    = [[Toronto]]\n |issn        = 1198-7235\n |oclc        = 679784246\n |date        = 2 September 2008\n |access-date  = 25 February 2011\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110607072040/http://www.chartattack.com/news/59800/saint-alvia-shorten-name\n |archive-date = 7 June 2011\n |url-status     = dead}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"junoawards.ca\"><!--only stated one of two nom's in lead section -->\n{{cite web\n| url         = http://junoawards.ca/database/artist-summary/?artist_name=Saint+Alvia\n| title       = Artist Summary\n| work        = Juno Awards Database\n| publisher   = [[Canadian Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]\n| archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110706184438/http://junoawards.ca/database/artist-summary/?artist_name=Saint+Alvia\n| archivedate = 6 July 2011\n| accessdate  = 25 February 2011\n| postscript  = . \n}}\n</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Alvia}}\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Canadian indie rock groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from the Regional Municipality of Halton]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2013]]\n[[Category:2005 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:2013 disestablishments in Ontario]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Saint Alvia\n| image                 =\n| caption            =\n| image_size            =\n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = The Saint Alvia Cartel\n| origin              = [[Burlington, Ontario|Burlington]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]\n| genre               = [[Rock music|Rock]]<br />[[Punk rock|Punk]]<br />[[Reggae]]\n| years_active        = 2005\u20132013\n| label               = [[Stomp Records|Stomp]]<br />[[Warner Music Canada]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Jersey (band)|Jersey]], [[Grade (band)|Grade]], [[Boys Night Out (band)|Boys Night Out]], The Video Dead (band)\n| website                 = [http://www.saintalvia.com Saint Alvia]\n| current_members     = Greg Taylor<br />Ben Rispin<br />Matt Richmond<br />Greg Fisher<br />Jon Laurin<br />Adam Michael\n}}\n\n'''Saint Alvia''', formerly '''The Saint Alvia Cartel''',<ref name=\"chartattack.com\"/> was a band formed in 2005 from [[Burlington, Ontario|Burlington]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]].  The band's self-titled debut album was nominated for a [[Juno Award for Rock Album of the Year]] at the [[2008 Juno Awards]].<ref name=\"junoawards.ca\"/>\n\n==History==\nSaint Alvia was formed by Rob Pasalic (formerly of [[Boys Night Out (band)|Boys Night Out]]) and Greg Taylor (formerly of [[Jersey (band)|Jersey]] and [[Grade (band)|Grade]]). The band is named after [[Ernest Alvia Smith]], Canada's last living recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]] for valor in World War II.\n\nWith roots in punk rock, the band drew inspiration from other genres which included rock and roll, blues, soul, dancehall reggae, country, new wave and hip hop. After recording and releasing demo tracks via MySpace in 2006, the band was signed to Montreal's Stomp Records and released their self-titled debut album in May 2006. The lead single \"Don't Wanna Wait Forever\" was released in the summer of 2007 and went into the Top 20 for Modern Rock Radio in Canada.\n\nThe band followed the 2007 release with 2008's critically acclaimed ''Between the Lines''.\n\nSaint Alvia played their final show on 7 December 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Destrukto|title=Burlington\u2019s Saint Alvia announce farewell show and final album|url=http://www.canadianmusicnews.com/zine/2013/12/06/new-releases/burlingtons-saint-alvia-announce-farewell-show-and-final-album/|website=Canadian Music News|accessdate=31 August 2016|date=6 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThey reunited [at least] one last time for [[Walk off the Earth]]'s Mike Taylor's Memorial and Tribute Concert<ref>{{cite news |title=Watch Mike \"Beard Guy\" Taylor Memorial and Tribute Concert |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F15MFWSafFY |accessdate=15 February 2019 |publisher=CBC Music}}</ref>\n\n==Members==\n* Greg Taylor - Vocals / Guitar\n* Ben Rispin - Vocals\n* Matt Richmond - Drums / Vocals\n* Greg Fisher - Guitar / Vocals\n* Jon Laurin - Keyboards\n* Adam Michael - Bass, Backing Vocals\n\n==Former members==\n* Brandon Bliss - Keyboards / Vocals\n* Rob Pasalic - Vocals / Guitar\n* Chuck Coles - Bass\n* Mike Casarin - Bass\n\n==Additional musicians==\n* Fatty McGinty of the Creepshow- Trombone (Try To Forget)\n* John Coombs of The Next Best Thing - Trumpet (Try To Forget)\n* Adam Michaels  - Guitar (Stones On The Road)\n* Jon Atley - Bongoes (Don't Wanna Wait Forever)\n* Laura Jane Bradfield - Vocals (Blonde Kryptonite)\n'''Between The Lines'''\n* Fatty McGinty of The Creepshow - Trombone (Decadencia De Civilizacion, Roll With it)\n* Ricky Snips of The Snips - Trumpet (Decadencia De Civilizacion, Roll With it,Mornings In Feng Tu)\n* Wade Mcneil of Alexisonfire/Black Lungs - Additional Vocals ( Mornings in Feng Tu)\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n*''The Saint Alvia Cartel - 4 song demo'' (2006 - Self Released)\n*''The Saint Alvia Cartel'' (2007 - Stomp Records)\n*''Between The Lines'' (2008 - Stomp Records)\n*''Jonxer 7-inch'' (2010 - Paper and Plastic)\n*''Static Psalms'' (2013 - Divergent Recordings)\n\n===Compilations===\n*''Borrowed Tunes - A Neil Young Tribute'' (Thrasher)\n*'' Juiceboxdotcom.com compilation - Don't Wanna Wait Forever'' ( Phil B's Sunshine Remix)\n\n===Singles===\n\n* ''Don't Wanna Wait Forever''\n* ''Time To Go''\n* ''Blonde Kryptonite''\n* ''Between The Lines''\n* ''Walk Before You Run DMC''\n* ''Romeo''\n* ''Mothers Day''\n* ''Define Me''\n\n==Awards==\n* [[2009 MuchMusic Video Awards]]: Best Post-Production ( The Saint Alvia Cartel \u2013 \"Blonde Kryptonite\" (post-production: Nick Flook, Mike Sevigny & Jeff Middleton)) - Nominated\n* [[Juno Awards of 2008]]: Rock Album of the Year(The Saint Alvia Cartel) - Nominated\n* [[Juno Awards of 2009]]: Best Video - Blonde Kryptonite ( Directed by Davin Black)-Nominated\n* [[2009 FU Awards]]: - Best FU song ( Romeo)- Nominated\n* [[2008 Hamilton Music Awards]]: Best Punk Album of the Year - Nominated\n* [[2008 Hamilton Music Awards]]: Video of The Year ( Between The Lines Directed by Davin Black,Produced by Ben Rispin) - Nominated\n* [[2007 Hamilton Music Awards]]: Best New Band - Won\n\n==Interviews==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081013042022/http://www.torontomusicscene.ca/interviews/saint-alvia-s-new-album-out-next-tuesday-ups-the-pol.html Saint Alvia\u2019s new album out next Tuesday ups the politics] Interview with TorontoMusicScene.ca\n*[https://archive.is/20130115093940/http://www.exclaim.ca/articles/multiarticlesub.aspx?csid1=112&csid2=4&fid1=26077 Saint Alvia Cartel article] July 2007\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090104000425/http://hangout.altsounds.com/features/100217-saint-alvia-cartel-interview-with-greg-taylor.html Altsounds: interview]\n*[https://archive.is/20080509131758/http://www.truthexplosion.com/live/interviews/interviews.php?id=232 Truth Explosion: article]\n*[http://www.supernova.com/thesaintalviacartel Supernova: article]\n*[http://www.citynews.ca/news/news_19435.aspx City News: article]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of bands from Canada]]\n{{Portal|Music|Canada}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist\n| colwidth = 30em\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"chartattack.com\">\n{{cite news\n |title       = Saint Alvia Shorten Name\n |author      = Erik Leijon\n |url         = http://www.chartattack.com/news/59800/saint-alvia-shorten-name\n |agency      = {{URL|chartattack.com}}\n |newspaper   = [[Chart (magazine)|Chart]]\n |publisher   = Chart Communications\n |location    = [[Toronto]]\n |issn        = 1198-7235\n |oclc        = 679784246\n |date        = 2 September 2008\n |access-date  = 25 February 2011\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110607072040/http://www.chartattack.com/news/59800/saint-alvia-shorten-name\n |archive-date = 7 June 2011\n |url-status     = dead}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"junoawards.ca\"><!--only stated one of two nom's in lead section -->\n{{cite web\n| url         = http://junoawards.ca/database/artist-summary/?artist_name=Saint+Alvia\n| title       = Artist Summary\n| work        = Juno Awards Database\n| publisher   = [[Canadian Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]\n| archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110706184438/http://junoawards.ca/database/artist-summary/?artist_name=Saint+Alvia\n| archivedate = 6 July 2011\n| accessdate  = 25 February 2011\n| postscript  = . \n}}\n</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Alvia}}\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Canadian indie rock groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from the Regional Municipality of Halton]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2013]]\n[[Category:2005 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:2013 disestablishments in Ontario]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Alvia"}
{"title_page": "Balls Pond Road Cemetery", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date= March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox cemetery\n| name        = Balls Pond Road Cemetery (Kingsbury Road Cemetery)\n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| map_type    = \n| map_size    = \n| map_caption = \n| coordinates = \n| established = 1843\n| country     = England\n| location    = Kingsbury Road, [[Dalston]] ([[London Borough of Islington]])\n| type        = Jewish\n| style       = \n| owner       = [[West London Synagogue]]\n| size        = 0.5 acres\n| graves      = 900\n| interments  = \n| website     = \n| findagrave  = [https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/2284789/kingsbury-road-cemetery Kingsbury Road Cemetery]\n| political   = \n}}\n'''Balls Pond Road Cemetery''', also known as '''Jewish (West London Reform) Cemetery,'''<ref name = \"Meller216\"/> '''Kingsbury Road Cemetery''', '''Balls Pond Burial Ground'''<ref name=\"Martin-Jones\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.apex.net.au/~tmj/balls-pond/ |title=Balls Pond Burial Ground |last=Martin-Jones |first=Tony |date=25 November 2015 |website=www.apex.net.au |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> and '''The Jewish Burial Ground''',<ref name = \"Gardens\"/> is  a  Jewish cemetery on Kingsbury Road, [[W postcode area |London W1]]. It was founded in 1843 and is owned by [[West London Synagogue]].<ref name = \"Meller216\">{{cite book|authors= Meller, Hugh; Parsons, Brian|title= London Cemeteries: an illustrated guide and gazetteer|publisher= [[The History Press]]|date= 2008 |page = 216|ISBN=978-0-7509-4622-3}}</ref> The last burial was in 1951.<ref name = \"Gardens\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/gardens-online-record.php?ID=ISL041 |title= The Jewish Burial Ground |website=[[London Gardens Online]] |publisher=[[London Parks and Gardens Trust]] |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> Prominent early members of the West London Synagogue, such as the de Stern, [[Goldsmid family|Goldsmid]] and [[Mocatta]] families, are buried in this cemetery.<ref name=\"Parks & Gardens\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.parksandgardens.org/places/the-jewish-burial-ground-islington |title=The Jewish Burial Ground, Islington |website=Parks & Gardens |publisher=Hestercombe Gardens Trust |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable burials==\n[[File:David Woolf Marks.jpg|120px| thumb|Reverend [[David Woolf Marks]]]] \nPeople buried at the cemetery include:\n* Sir [[Isaac Lyon Goldsmid]], 1st Baronet (1778\u20131859), financier and one of the leading figures in the Jewish emancipation in the United Kingdom<ref name = \"Meller216\"/>\n*Sir [[Julian Goldsmid]], 3rd Baronet (1838\u20131896), lawyer, businessman, Liberal (later Liberal Unionist) MP, Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of London]] and art collector<ref name = \"Meller216\"/>\n*[[Amy Levy]] (1861\u20131889), essayist, poet, and novelist, who was the first Jewish woman at [[Cambridge University]] and the first Jewish woman to be cremated in England; her ashes were interred at this cemetery<ref name=\"Medd\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=28rZCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA127&lpg=PA127&dq=west+london+synagogue+balls+pond+road&source=bl&ots=CPH-nv0Jtv&sig=ACfU3U20fguC4hulqjaD2WJcxC2r1J4pqQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj6qvGevcXoAhWPN8AKHRejCQs4ChDoATAIegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=west%20london%20synagogue%20balls%20pond%20road&f=false|title=The Cambridge Companion to Lesbian Literature |date=2015 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |editor-last=Medd |editor-first=Jodie |pages=127|ISBN= 978-1-107-05400-4}}</ref>\n*[[Joseph Moses Levy]] (1812\u20131888), newspaper editor and publisher, who was chief proprietor of  ''[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]'' and also managed ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''<ref name = \"Meller216\"/>\n*[[James Joseph Sylvester]] (1814\u20131897), mathematician and [[University of Oxford]] professor. He made fundamental contributions to [[matrix theory]], [[invariant theory]], [[number theory]], [[partition theory]] and [[combinatorics]]. He played a leadership role in American mathematics in the later half of the 19th century as a professor at the [[Johns Hopkins University]] and as founder of the ''[[American Journal of Mathematics]]''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Biographical Index of Former Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh 1783\u20132002|date=July 2006|publisher=The Royal Society of Edinburgh|isbn=0-902-198-84-X|url=https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/biographical_index/fells_indexp2.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"UCL\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/economics/about-department/famous-economists/james-joseph-sylvester-1814-1897 |title=James Joseph Sylvester (1814\u20131897) |publisher=[[University College London]] |access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n*Reverend [[David Woolf Marks]] (1811\u20131909), Hebrew scholar and minister, who was the first religious leader of the West London Synagogue<ref name=\"Marks\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cemeteryscribes.com/getperson.php?personID=I9088&tree=Cemeteries | title=MARKS Rev. Prof David Woolf [David b Benjamin Ze'ev] 1811\u20131909 | publisher=Cemetery Scribes | date=22 August 2009 | accessdate=31 March 2013}}</ref>\n*[[David Mocatta]] (1806\u20131882), architect of railway stations and synagogues, and a founder of the West London Synagogue<ref name = \"Meller216\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|London}}\n\n[[Category:1843 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in London]]\n[[Category:Jewish cemeteries in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Judaism in London]]\n[[Category:Religion in the London Borough of Islington]]\n\n{{UK-cemetery-stub}}\n{{Jewish-cemetery-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date= March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox cemetery\n| name        = Balls Pond Road Cemetery (Kingsbury Road Cemetery)\n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| map_type    = \n| map_size    = \n| map_caption = \n| coordinates = \n| established = 1843\n| country     = England\n| location    = Kingsbury Road, [[Dalston]] ([[London Borough of Islington]])\n| type        = Jewish\n| style       = \n| owner       = [[West London Synagogue]]\n| size        = 0.5 acres\n| graves      = 900\n| interments  = \n| website     = \n| findagrave  = [https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/2284789/kingsbury-road-cemetery Kingsbury Road Cemetery]\n| political   = \n}}\n'''Balls Pond Road Cemetery''', also known as '''Jewish (West London Reform) Cemetery,'''<ref name = \"Meller216\"/> '''Kingsbury Road Cemetery''', '''Balls Pond Burial Ground'''<ref name=\"Martin-Jones\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.apex.net.au/~tmj/balls-pond/ |title=Balls Pond Burial Ground |last=Martin-Jones |first=Tony |date=25 November 2015 |website=www.apex.net.au |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> and '''The Jewish Burial Ground''',<ref name = \"Gardens\"/> is  a  Jewish cemetery on Kingsbury Road, [[W postcode area |London W1]]. It was founded in 1843 and is owned by [[West London Synagogue]].<ref name = \"Meller216\">{{cite book|authors= Meller, Hugh; Parsons, Brian|title= London Cemeteries: an illustrated guide and gazetteer|publisher= [[The History Press]]|date= 2008 |page = 216|ISBN=978-0-7509-4622-3}}</ref> The last burial was in 1951.<ref name = \"Gardens\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/gardens-online-record.php?ID=ISL041 |title= The Jewish Burial Ground |website=[[London Gardens Online]] |publisher=[[London Parks and Gardens Trust]] |access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> Prominent early members of the West London Synagogue, such as the de Stern, [[Goldsmid family|Goldsmid]] and [[Mocatta]] families, are buried in this cemetery.<ref name=\"Parks & Gardens\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.parksandgardens.org/places/the-jewish-burial-ground-islington |title=The Jewish Burial Ground, Islington |website=Parks & Gardens |publisher=Hestercombe Gardens Trust |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable burials==\n[[File:David Woolf Marks.jpg|120px| thumb|Reverend [[David Woolf Marks]]]] \nPeople buried at the cemetery include:\n* Sir [[Isaac Lyon Goldsmid]], 1st Baronet (1778\u20131859), financier and one of the leading figures in the Jewish emancipation in the United Kingdom<ref name = \"Meller216\"/>\n*Sir [[Julian Goldsmid]], 3rd Baronet (1838\u20131896), lawyer, businessman, Liberal (later Liberal Unionist) MP, Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of London]] and art collector<ref name = \"Meller216\"/>\n*[[Amy Levy]] (1861\u20131889), essayist, poet, and novelist, who was the first Jewish woman at [[Cambridge University]] and the first Jewish woman to be cremated in England; her ashes were interred at this cemetery<ref name=\"Medd\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=28rZCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA127&lpg=PA127&dq=west+london+synagogue+balls+pond+road&source=bl&ots=CPH-nv0Jtv&sig=ACfU3U20fguC4hulqjaD2WJcxC2r1J4pqQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj6qvGevcXoAhWPN8AKHRejCQs4ChDoATAIegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=west%20london%20synagogue%20balls%20pond%20road&f=false|title=The Cambridge Companion to Lesbian Literature |date=2015 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |editor-last=Medd |editor-first=Jodie |pages=127|ISBN= 978-1-107-05400-4}}</ref>\n*[[Joseph Moses Levy]] (1812\u20131888), newspaper editor and publisher, who was chief proprietor of  ''[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]'' and also managed ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''<ref name = \"Meller216\"/>\n*[[James Joseph Sylvester]] (1814\u20131897), mathematician and [[University of Oxford]] professor. He made fundamental contributions to [[matrix theory]], [[invariant theory]], [[number theory]], [[partition theory]] and [[combinatorics]]. He played a leadership role in American mathematics in the later half of the 19th century as a professor at the [[Johns Hopkins University]] and as founder of the ''[[American Journal of Mathematics]]''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Biographical Index of Former Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh 1783\u20132002|date=July 2006|publisher=The Royal Society of Edinburgh|isbn=0-902-198-84-X|url=https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/biographical_index/fells_indexp2.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"UCL\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/economics/about-department/famous-economists/james-joseph-sylvester-1814-1897 |title=James Joseph Sylvester (1814 - 1897) |publisher=[[University College London]] |access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n*Reverend [[David Woolf Marks]] (1811\u20131909), Hebrew scholar and minister, who was the first religious leader of the West London Synagogue<ref name=\"Marks\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cemeteryscribes.com/getperson.php?personID=I9088&tree=Cemeteries | title=MARKS Rev. Prof David Woolf [David b Benjamin Ze'ev] 1811\u20131909 | publisher=Cemetery Scribes | date=22 August 2009 | accessdate=31 March 2013}}</ref>\n*[[David Mocatta]] (1806\u20131882), architect of railway stations and synagogues, and a founder of the West London Synagogue<ref name = \"Meller216\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|London}}\n\n[[Category:1843 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in London]]\n[[Category:Jewish cemeteries in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Judaism in London]]\n[[Category:Religion in the London Borough of Islington]]\n\n{{UK-cemetery-stub}}\n{{Jewish-cemetery-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Headhitter", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balls_Pond_Road_Cemetery"}
{"title_page": "Eaton Hotel Hong Kong", "text_new": "''Not to be confused with the [[Carey House (Wichita, Kansas)]], also known as Eaton Hotel''\n\n{{short description|Hotel in Kowloon, Hong Kong}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name                = Eaton HK\n| native_name         = \u9999\u6e2f\u9038\u6771\u9152\u5e97\n| native_name_lang    = zh_yue\n| logo                = \n| logo_size           = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| image               = Hong Kong 2013 various photos 32.JPG\n| image_size          = 250px\n| image_alt           = <!-- or | alt = -->\n| image_caption       = Eaton HK\n| map_type            = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| map_size            = \n| map_dot_label       = \n| map_dot_mark        = \n| relief              = \n| former_names        = \n| alternate_names     = \n| etymology           = \n| status              = \n| cancelled           = \n| topped_out          = \n| building_type       = \n| architectural_style = \n| classification      = \n| location            = \n| address             = 380 [[Nathan Road]] in [[Kowloon]]\n| location_city       = [[Hong Kong]]\n| location_country    = \n| coordinates         = \n| altitude            = \n| current_tenants     = \n| namesake            = \n| groundbreaking_date = \n| start_date          = \n| stop_date           = \n| est_completion      = \n| topped_out_date     = \n| completion_date     = \n| opened_date         = 1990\n| inauguration_date   = \n| relocated_date      = \n| renovation_date     = 2018\n| closing_date        = \n| demolition_date     = <!-- or | destruction_date    = -->\n| cost                = \n| ren_cost            = \n| client              = \n| owner               = \n| landlord            = \n| affiliation         = \n| height              = \n| architectural       = \n| tip                 = \n| antenna_spire       = \n| roof                = \n| top_floor           = \n| observatory         = \n| diameter            = \n| circumference       = \n| weight              = \n| other_dimensions    = \n| structural_system   = \n| material            = \n| size                = \n| floor_count         = \n| floor_area          = \n| elevator_count      = \n| grounds_area        = \n| architect           = \n| architecture_firm   = \n| developer           = \n| engineer            = \n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer   = \n| civil_engineer      = \n| other_designers     = \n| quantity_surveyor   = \n| main_contractor     = \n| awards              = \n| designations        = \n| known_for           = \n| ren_architect       = \n| ren_firm            = \n| ren_engineer        = \n| ren_str_engineer    = \n| ren_serv_engineer   = \n| ren_civ_engineer    = \n| ren_oth_designers   = \n| ren_qty_surveyor    = \n| ren_contractor      = \n| ren_awards          = \n| rooms               = 465 Rooms, 2 Suites\n| parking             =  \n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| embed               = \n| embedded            = \n| references          = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n{{Chinese|t=\u9999\u6e2f\u9038\u6771\u9152\u5e97|s=\u9999\u6e2f\u9038\u4e1c\u9152\u5e97|j=hoeng1 gong2 jat6 dung1 zau2 dim3|p=Xi\u0101ngg\u01ceng Y\u00ecd\u014dng Ji\u01d4di\u00e0n}}\n'''Eaton HK''' \u00a0({{zh|t=\u9999\u6e2f\u9038\u6771\u9152\u5e97}}), owned by the [[Great Eagle Holdings|Great Eagle Group]], is a four-star [[hotel]] located at 380 [[Nathan Road]] in [[Kowloon]], between [[Jordan, Hong Kong|Jordan]] and [[Yau Ma Tei]], near the [[Temple Street Night Market]] and the Jade Market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smarttravelasia.com/hkhotel.htm|title=Hong Kong business hotels|publisher=SmartTravel Asia|accessdate=2007-11-01}}</ref> In fall 2018, Eaton Hong Kong was rebranded as Eaton HK, a hotel under Eaton Workshop. Following the co-living concept pioneered in the UK and US by hotel-[[co-working space]] organisations like The Collective in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://commercialobserver.com/2020/02/co-living-company-the-collective-moving-nyc-offices-to-soho/|title=Co-Living Company The Collective Moving NYC Offices to Soho|last=February 27|first=Nicholas Rizzi|last2=Pm|first2=2020 1:27|date=2020-02-27|website=Commercial Observer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> Eaton Workshop is part of the portfolio of Hong Kong based [[Great Eagle Holdings]] Ltd, which is also the parent company of [[Langham Hospitality Group]], both helmed by Chairman, Ka Shui Lo, billionaire son of the late real estate tycoon Lo Ying-shek.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/property/hong-kong-china/article/2095568/who-deserves-more-lo-family-locked-nasty-feud|title=Who deserves more? The Lo family is locked in a nasty feud|date=2017-05-24|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==Guest rooms and suites==\nEaton HK has 465 rooms in a range of sizes and configurations, ranging from 172 sq. ft. to 603 sq. ft.  \u00a0\n\n==Meeting and function facilities==\nEaton HK has the following meeting and function spaces:  Three ballrooms/function rooms capable of accommodating meetings for up to 250 persons or up to 18 tables banquet style, ranging from 690sq.ft. to 2570sq.ft. Each of the ballrooms can be divided into smaller ballrooms to facilitate events such as meetings, seminars, exhibitions or dinners. Private theatre Kino includes full AV setup and LCD projector, open floor plan, and other facilities perfectly suited to a wide range of settings, styles and formats.  \n\nThe hotel includes an art gallery, \u201cTomorrow Maybe,\u201d that showcases a rotating art exhibition of local and international talent, as well as a three-story art installation, a built-in radio station, an screening room, live music venues\u2014 for performances, panels, workshops, readings, and more\u2014 and artist residency rooms outfitted as professional visual arts and recording studios.\n\n==Dining facilities==\nEaton HK has food and beverage options, including the following restaurants: Yat Tung Heen, a one Michelin-starred Chinese restaurant with an extensive menu of traditional Chinese cuisine, including Cantonese specialities and classic dim sum; The Astor, an all-day international dining restaurant with eight live cooking stations, offering international cuisine in a retro setting; Terrible Baby, bar, outdoor terrace and performance venue that features cocktails, wine, a selection of spirits, and bar snacks. Eaton Food Hall, A community food market boasting 10 food stalls, a neighborhood bar, and built-in radio station. \n\n==Transportation ==\nThe hotel is a five-minute walk from [[Jordan station]]. Many buses also ply Nathan Road.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Eaton Hotel Hong Kong}}\n*{{Official website|https://www.eatonworkshop.com/hotel/hong-kong}}\n\n{{Nathan Road}}\n{{Yau Tsim Mong District}}\n{{Hotels in Hong Kong}}\n{{coord|22.3081|114.1718|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Hotels in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Yau Ma Tei]]\n\n{{HongKong-struct-stub}}\n{{Asia-hotel-stub}}\n", "text_old": "''Not to be confused with the [[Carey House (Wichita, Kansas)]], also known as Eaton Hotel''\n\n{{short description|Hotel in Kowloon, Hong Kong}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name                = Eaton HK\n| native_name         = \u9999\u6e2f\u9038\u6771\u9152\u5e97\n| native_name_lang    = zh_yue\n| logo                = \n| logo_size           = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| image               = Hong Kong 2013 various photos 32.JPG\n| image_size          = 250px\n| image_alt           = <!-- or | alt = -->\n| image_caption       = Eaton HK\n| map_type            = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| map_size            = \n| map_dot_label       = \n| map_dot_mark        = \n| relief              = \n| former_names        = \n| alternate_names     = \n| etymology           = \n| status              = \n| cancelled  