ing             =  \n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| embed               = \n| embedded            = \n| references          = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n{{Chinese|t=\u9999\u6e2f\u9038\u6771\u9152\u5e97|s=\u9999\u6e2f\u9038\u4e1c\u9152\u5e97|j=hoeng1 gong2 jat6 dung1 zau2 dim3|p=Xi\u0101ngg\u01ceng Y\u00ecd\u014dng Ji\u01d4di\u00e0n}}\n'''Eaton HK''' \u00a0({{zh|t=\u9999\u6e2f\u9038\u6771\u9152\u5e97}}), owned by the [[Great Eagle Holdings|Great Eagle Group]], is a four-star [[hotel]] located at 380 [[Nathan Road]] in [[Kowloon]], between [[Jordan, Hong Kong|Jordan]] and [[Yau Ma Tei]], near the [[Temple Street Night Market]] and the Jade Market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smarttravelasia.com/hkhotel.htm|title=Hong Kong business hotels|publisher=SmartTravel Asia|accessdate=2007-11-01}}</ref> In fall 2018, Eaton Hong Kong was rebranded as Eaton HK, a hotel under Eaton Workshop. Following the co-living concept pioneered in the UK and US by hotel-[[co-working space]] organisations like The Collective in 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://commercialobserver.com/2020/02/co-living-company-the-collective-moving-nyc-offices-to-soho/|title=Co-Living Company The Collective Moving NYC Offices to Soho|last=February 27|first=Nicholas Rizzi|last2=Pm|first2=2020 1:27|date=2020-02-27|website=Commercial Observer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>. Eaton Workshop is part of the portfolio of Hong Kong based [[Great Eagle Holdings]] Ltd, which is also the parent company of [[Langham Hospitality Group]], both helmed by Chairman, Ka Shui Lo, Billionaire son of the late real estate tycoon Lo Ying-shek<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/property/hong-kong-china/article/2095568/who-deserves-more-lo-family-locked-nasty-feud|title=Who deserves more? The Lo family is locked in a nasty feud|date=2017-05-24|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>. \n\n==Guest rooms and suites==\nEaton HK has 465 rooms in a range of sizes and configurations, ranging from 172 sq. ft. to 603 sq. ft.  \u00a0\n\n==Meeting and function facilities==\nEaton HK has the following meeting and function spaces:  Three ballrooms/function rooms capable of accommodating meetings for up to 250 persons or up to 18 tables banquet style, ranging from 690sq.ft. to 2570sq.ft. Each of the ballrooms can be divided into smaller ballrooms to facilitate events such as meetings, seminars, exhibitions or dinners. Private theatre Kino includes full AV setup and LCD projector, open floor plan, and other facilities perfectly suited to a wide range of settings, styles and formats.  \n\nThe hotel includes an art gallery, \u201cTomorrow Maybe,\u201d that showcases a rotating art exhibition of local and international talent, as well as a three-story art installation, a built-in radio station, an screening room, live music venues\u2014 for performances, panels, workshops, readings, and more\u2014 and artist residency rooms outfitted as professional visual arts and recording studios.\n\n==Dining facilities==\nEaton HK has food and beverage options, including the following restaurants: Yat Tung Heen, a one Michelin-starred Chinese restaurant with an extensive menu of traditional Chinese cuisine, including Cantonese specialities and classic dim sum; The Astor, an all-day international dining restaurant with eight live cooking stations, offering international cuisine in a retro setting; Terrible Baby, bar, outdoor terrace and performance venue that features cocktails, wine, a selection of spirits, and bar snacks. Eaton Food Hall, A community food market boasting 10 food stalls, a neighborhood bar, and built-in radio station. \n\n==Transportation ==\nThe hotel is a five-minute walk from [[Jordan station]]. Many buses also ply Nathan Road.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Eaton Hotel Hong Kong}}\n*{{Official website|https://www.eatonworkshop.com/hotel/hong-kong}}\n\n{{Nathan Road}}\n{{Yau Tsim Mong District}}\n{{Hotels in Hong Kong}}\n{{coord|22.3081|114.1718|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Hotels in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Yau Ma Tei]]\n\n{{HongKong-struct-stub}}\n{{Asia-hotel-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Greyjoy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eaton_Hotel_Hong_Kong"}
{"title_page": "Shayne Topp", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2018}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=July 2019}}\n}}\n{{Infobox actor\n| name               = Shayne Topp\n| birth_name         = Shayne Robert Topp<ref name=\"r\u00e9sum\u00e9\" />\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1991|9|14|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Phoenix, Arizona]], U.S.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n| residence          = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[Arizona State University]] (BA)\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actor|Internet personality}}\n| height             = 5' 8\"\n| years_active       = 2006-present\n| image              = \n}}\n'''Shayne Robert Topp''' (born September 14, 1991) is an American actor and comedian most known for his roles on the [[YouTube]] channel [[Smosh]], Matt Bradley in ''[[The Goldbergs (2013 TV series)|The Goldbergs]]'', [[Disney Channel]]'s ''[[iCarly]]'' and [[Disney Channel]]'s ''[[So Random!]]'' He is also known for his [[improvisational theatre|improv]] and [[voice acting|vocal]] work. \n\n==Early life==\nShayne was born on September 14th to Catherine Topp (n\u00e9e Person) and Robert Royal Topp,<ref>{{cite web|title=Twitter post by the subject of the article|url=https://twitter.com/supershayne/status/763148254246600704|website=Twitter.com|accessdate=December 15, 2017|date=9 August 2016}}{{Verify source|date=July 2019}}</ref> a fighter pilot.<ref>{{cite web|title=Instagram post by the subject of the article|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BbXZgchnOhI/|website=Instagram.com|accessdate=December 15, 2017|date=11 November 2017}}{{Verify source|date=July 2019}}</ref> His grandfather, Wayne Topp, was also a fighter pilot. Topp participated in an acting class with his friend (and fellow [[Smosh]] member) Noah Grossman, taught by the mother of [[Laura Marano]].\n\n==Career==\nShayne also has experience in [[Theater of the United States|theatre]] performances, starring in \"The Best Christmas Pageant Ever\" at Wonderworks Theatre Co. and \"Willie Wonka and the Chocolate Factory\" at Highland Lakes Theatre (as the title role).<ref name=\"r\u00e9sum\u00e9\">{{cite web|title=The Subject's actual Resume|url=http://www.lacasting.com/resume/resumeprint.asp?crypt=diagnimephhohdjjcljpdljngcoodjmbdfaoonlehdedeegb|website=LA Casting|accessdate=December 15, 2017}}{{Verify source|date=July 2019}}</ref> Additionally, he has appeared in commercials.<ref name=\"r\u00e9sum\u00e9\" />\n\nHe went on to win the Jury Prize at the 2009 Los Angeles Film Festival for his performance in ''[[Dear Lemon Lima]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Han |first1=Angie |title=\u2018Dear Lemon Lima\u2019 Trailer |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/dear-lemon-lima-trailer/ |website=www.slashfilm.com |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |language=en |date=13 February 2011}}</ref> He was also nominated for \"Exciting New Face (Male)\" at the 2014 Young Hollywood Awards. Originally deciding to move away in 2015 due to a lack of work, he was convinced by Noah Grossman to audition for the cast of [[Smosh]], which he remains a part since 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Spangler |first1=Todd |title=\u2018Smosh\u2019 New Comedy Shows Lead Defy Media\u2019s Fall Slate of Original Series |url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/smosh-defy-fall-programming-1201877480/ |website=Variety |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |language=en |date=4 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hamedy |first1=Saba |title=How two high school friends built a YouTube empire |url=https://mashable.com/2017/04/16/the-rise-of-smosh-anthony-padilla-ian-hecox/ |website=Mashable |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |language=en |date=16 April 2017}}</ref> Smosh\u2019s parent company Defy Media went bankrupt in late 2018, however Topp and the rest of the cast still continued to make videos; and in early 2019 it was announced that Smosh was purchased by [[Mythical Entertainment]].\nAs of Late 2019, Topp continues to appear in the majority of all videos (including Main, Pit, and often Games). \n\nIn 2019, Topp graduated from [[Arizona State University]]'s online campus with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[Psychology]], a degree that he's been pursuing since 2009. A surprise dedication and mock graduation ceremony was held by the Smosh crew and was uploaded to Smosh Pit in December 2019.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width=95%; font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Role\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2006 || ''Moonpie'' || John Paul ||\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[iCarly]]'' || Philip Brownley || Episode: iMight Switch Schools\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Dear Lemon Lima]]'' || Philip Georgey ||\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Eli Stone]]'' || Young Nathan Stone || Pilot\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2011 || ''[[Love Bites (TV series)|Love Bites]]'' || Ian || Episode: Too Much Information\n|-\n|''All Kids Count|| Corey ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2012 || ''[[Fred: The Show]]'' || Steve || Episode: Expired Cow\n|-\n|''[[So Random!]] || Shayne Zabo ||\n|-\n|''Hi, Lillian'' || Dylan || Short\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2013 || ''The Violation'' || Oscar Hel || Short\n|-\n|''[[AwesomenessTV]]'' ||  || Episode: Swag Master J: Swagify for School\n|-\n|''First'' || Rick || Short\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2014 || ''Re-Writes'' || || Short\n|-\n|''[[Sam & Cat]]'' || Vance Anderson || Episode: #StuckInABox\n|-\n|''[[What's Next for Sarah?]]'' || Chad || Episode 2\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2015 || ''[[Switched at Birth (TV series)|Switched at Birth]]'' || Taylor Halsted || Episode: I Lock the Door Upon Myself\n|-\n|''[[A Sort of Homecoming (film)|A Sort of Homecoming]]'' || Dylan Conti ||\n|-\n|''[[Henry Danger]]'' || Dennis || Episode: Captain Jerk\n|-\n| 2015-''present'' || ''[[Smosh]]'' || Various characters || Main Cast Member; Recurring appearance in sketches and events\n|-\n| 2015 || ''Astrid Clover'' || Cop with Taser || Episode: Photo Fads\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2016 || ''Boys on Film 14: Worlds Collide'' || Oscar Heim || Segment: \"The Violation\"\n|-\n|''Cell Outs'' ||  ||\n|-\n| 2017-''present''  || ''[[The Goldbergs (2013 TV series)|The Goldbergs]]'' || Matt Bradley<ref>{{cite web |author1=BWW News Desk |title=Scoop: THE GOLDBERGS on ABC - Today, November 1, 2017 |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Scoop-THE-GOLDBERGS-on-ABC-Today-November-1-2017-20171031 |website=BroadwayWorld.com |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |language=en |date=1 November 2017}}</ref> || Recurring \n|-\n|2019 || ''[[Schooled (TV series)|Schooled]]'' || Matt Bradley<ref>{{Citation|title=Schooled - Season 1 Episode 13|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/schooled/s01/e13|language=en|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref> || Episode: Dr. Barry\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 2009\n| Role in ''[[Dear Lemon Lima]]''\n| Los Angeles Film Festival (Jury Prize) - Outstanding Performance\n| {{won}} \n|-\n| 2010\n| Role in ''[[Dear Lemon Lima]]''\n| Method Fest - Best Ensemble Cast\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2014\n| Role in ''[[Dear Lemon Lima]]''\n| Young Hollywood Awards - New Exciting Face (Male)\n| {{nom}} \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|2425775}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Topp, Shayne}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2018}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=July 2019}}\n}}\n{{Infobox actor\n| name               = Shayne Topp\n| birth_name         = Shayne Robert Topp<ref name=\"r\u00e9sum\u00e9\" />\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1991|9|14|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Phoenix, Arizona]], U.S.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n| residence          = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[Arizona State University]] (BA)\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actor|Internet personality}}\n| height             = 5' 8\"\n| years_active       = 2006-present\n| image              = \n}}\n'''Shayne Robert Topp''' (born September 14, 1991) is an American actor and comedian most known for his roles on [[Smosh]], Matt Bradley in ''[[The Goldbergs (2013 TV series)|The Goldbergs]]'' and [[Disney Channel]]'s ''[[So Random!]]'' He is also known for his [[improvisational theatre|improv]] and [[voice acting|vocal]] work.\n\n==Early life==\nShayne was born on September 14th to Catherine Topp (n\u00e9e Person) and Robert Royal Topp,<ref>{{cite web|title=Twitter post by the subject of the article|url=https://twitter.com/supershayne/status/763148254246600704|website=Twitter.com|accessdate=December 15, 2017|date=9 August 2016}}{{Verify source|date=July 2019}}</ref> a fighter pilot.<ref>{{cite web|title=Instagram post by the subject of the article|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BbXZgchnOhI/|website=Instagram.com|accessdate=December 15, 2017|date=11 November 2017}}{{Verify source|date=July 2019}}</ref> His grandfather, Wayne Topp, was also a fighter pilot. Topp participated in an acting class with his friend (and fellow [[Smosh]] member) Noah Grossman, taught by the mother of [[Laura Marano]].\n\n==Career==\nShayne also has experience in [[Theater of the United States|theatre]] performances, starring in \"The Best Christmas Pageant Ever\" at Wonderworks Theatre Co. and \"Willie Wonka and the Chocolate Factory\" at Highland Lakes Theatre (as the title role).<ref name=\"r\u00e9sum\u00e9\">{{cite web|title=The Subject's actual Resume|url=http://www.lacasting.com/resume/resumeprint.asp?crypt=diagnimephhohdjjcljpdljngcoodjmbdfaoonlehdedeegb|website=LA Casting|accessdate=December 15, 2017}}{{Verify source|date=July 2019}}</ref> Additionally, he has appeared in commercials.<ref name=\"r\u00e9sum\u00e9\" />\n\nHe went on to win the Jury Prize at the 2009 Los Angeles Film Festival for his performance in ''[[Dear Lemon Lima]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Han |first1=Angie |title=\u2018Dear Lemon Lima\u2019 Trailer |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/dear-lemon-lima-trailer/ |website=www.slashfilm.com |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |language=en |date=13 February 2011}}</ref> He was also nominated for \"Exciting New Face (Male)\" at the 2014 Young Hollywood Awards. Originally deciding to move away in 2015 due to a lack of work, he was convinced by Noah Grossman to audition for the cast of [[Smosh]], which he remains a part since 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Spangler |first1=Todd |title=\u2018Smosh\u2019 New Comedy Shows Lead Defy Media\u2019s Fall Slate of Original Series |url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/smosh-defy-fall-programming-1201877480/ |website=Variety |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |language=en |date=4 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hamedy |first1=Saba |title=How two high school friends built a YouTube empire |url=https://mashable.com/2017/04/16/the-rise-of-smosh-anthony-padilla-ian-hecox/ |website=Mashable |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |language=en |date=16 April 2017}}</ref> Smosh\u2019s parent company Defy Media went bankrupt in late 2018, however Topp and the rest of the cast still continued to make videos; and in early 2019 it was announced that Smosh was purchased by [[Mythical Entertainment]].\nAs of Late 2019, Topp continues to appear in the majority of all videos (including Main, Pit, and often Games). \n\nIn 2019, Topp graduated from [[Arizona State University]]'s online campus with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[Psychology]], a degree that he's been pursuing since 2009. A surprise dedication and mock graduation ceremony was held by the Smosh crew and was uploaded to Smosh Pit in December 2019.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width=95%; font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Role\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2006 || ''Moonpie'' || John Paul ||\n|-\n| 2008 